`Integer` class provides several utility methods to
convert numbers between different formats and data types. `toString()` converts an integer into its String representation,
while `toBinaryString()`, `toOctalString()`, and `toHexString()` convert a decimal number into binary, 
octal, and hexadecimal formats respectively. To convert a numeric String back into an integer, Java provides `valueOf()` and 
`parseInt()`. The `valueOf()` method returns an `Integer` object, whereas `parseInt()` returns a primitive `int`.
These methods are commonly used in Java for number conversion, data processing, and handling different number systems efficiently.







import java.util.*;
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
      String s=Integer.toString(10);
      System.out.println(s);
      String h=Integer.toBinaryString(15);
      System.out.println(h);
      
      int i=Integer.valueOf(h);//it willl return an object of the class
      System.out.println(i);
      
      int k=Integer.parseInt(h);//it will return dtye
      System.out.println(k);
      
      
      String r=Integer.toOctalString(15);
      System.out.println(r);
      
      String h1=Integer.toHexString(15);
      System.out.println(h1);
    }
}


